title: For Sale:  1895 Antique Double .410 Shotgun
postcontent: For sale is a very unique double barrel 410 shotgun called Rocket Special. It was made sometime between 1895 and 1915. It was made by Hopkins&Allen and was way ahead of its time. The shotgun was made specifically for Supplee Biddle Hardware in Philidelphia, Pennsulvania. This little shotgun has internal strikers instead of outside hammers. It also  has a tank safety on top of the receiver and the barrels are laminated steel and not damascus twist steel barrels. It also has a 3 inch chamber which was unheard of in those days.This gun is over 100 years old and I doubt that it was fired very many times. It is in very good condition and locks up tightly. It is a very unusual firearm to say the least.  I am firm on the price of $500.00 so don't email or call me unless you are serious. My number is:REDACTED so you can call or email me at Armslist. If you can read this post the item is still for sale. Thanks!

title: For Sale:  Colt 1917 45 Cal Revolver
postcontent: This is a like new condition Colt 1917 .45 caliber revolver. The serial number is 18607 located at the bottom of the grip. Overall condition of the firearms is excellent based on NRA Antique Firearm condition. The only problem is that it appears to have been completely restored to like new condition. I am not sure when or by whom it was done. I bought this firearm at an estate sale. The entire action of revolver is like using a brand new one. It has been meticously re-done and has a person's name "Robert Leib" engraved into the frame. I am not sure if this was a previous owner or the person who restored the firearm. The wood grips seem to be authentic for the period and it does have US Army Model 1917 stamped on the bottom of the grip. This gun is hard to rate because it is like a new firearm mechanically but has been restored which means from a collector perspective could lower the value. I am not a gun expert but this one is a clean version of the Colt 1917 that could be taken and fired. It has a 5 1/2 inch barrel. The following markings are on the barrel: On one side its marked "Colt DA 45", under the barrel is marked "United States Property" and on top has "COLTs PT FA MTG CO. Hartford, CT USA, PATD AUG 5, 1884, June 5 1900, July 4 1905." The cylinder has different serial numbers than on the handgrip. If you do research this seems to be typical for the 1917 models. The goverment uses the serial number on the grip as the tracking mechanism. The frame and cylinder has 170686 and below that number is 13118. The entire action of the firearms is solid, the cylinder does not turn freely, the action works as it should with the timing.Must have CCP or gun purchase permit.
